\f2 \cf2 questions:\
\
\
\
\
-- What originally inspired you to become involved in activism? What do you advocate for?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 There are many things that inspired me to become an organizer. Mainly, I saw problems that needed a second look. I come from a middle-class, Black, military family, and I l(ironically) learned a lot about organizational structures, hierarchies, and how few people are sometimes allowed to make decisions on behalf of too many. When I went to college, like many organizers, I was radicalized and politicized by other students on campus and people in the community where I went to school (UNCC). I participated in different campaigns about getting cops off of campus, trying to get the institution to divest from the PIC, paying the non-faculty campus workers more money, and raising awareness about anti Black and anti trans violence on and off campus. From there, I went to become more involved in the community outside of the campus. My organizing led me to ultimately organizing against cops and prisons. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
-- I am writing about Dataminr, a company that, among other things, has helped police in the past to keep an eye on protests by looking at the contents of protesters' publicly available social media feeds. Are you surprised that the Charlotte PD has a contract with this company? How do you feel about it?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 I am not surprised that CMPD has a contract with Dataminr. CMPD has relationships with many carceral entities. I feel that police must be defunded so that they are limited in the carceral relationships that they are able to maintain with entities like Dataminr, which are interested in surveillance and control. \cf2 \strokec2 \
\
-- What has your role in protesting been? What were you protesting specifically? When were you active in this role?\
\cf3 \strokec3 I have held many different roles at different types of actions including jail support hotline volunteer, direct action trainer, front-liner, social media point person, media contact, and an architect of Charlotte Uprising. I have protested for and against many different campaigns and causes including but not limited to protests in support of Justice for Palenstinian People, actions that support incarcerated individuals like call-ins, noise demonstrations, bail-outs, and fundraisers. I protest in support of access to abortion and bodily autonomy. I protest in support of poor people, Black disabled, trans, people. Campaigns that resist systems of incarceration and carceral logics are near and dear to me. I am also a professor at UNCC. I teach a Black Abolitionist Dreaming Course. I enjoy facilitating conversations about how we can build alternatives to police and prisons, how to organizer direct actions, and how to be an abortion doula. \cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf3 \strokec3 I have been protesting and learning and organizing in these ways since around 2011.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\
-- Now that things are quieter in terms of street protests themselves, what role do you currently play in the protest movement?\
\cf3 \strokec3 No Comment. \cf2 \strokec2  \
\
-- What is your day job? Does it overlap at all with your activism?\
\
\cf3 \strokec3 I don't have a day job. I was recently fired by Greenpeace USA. Please see this article: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://medium.com/@ashwilliamsclt/do-black-lives-really-matter-at-greenpeace-usa-3752f756bafc"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 https://medium.com/@ashwilliamsclt/do-black-lives-really-matter-at-greenpeace-usa-3752f756bafc}}\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf3 \strokec3 I am an adjunct faculty member at UNCC in the Women's and Gender Studies Department.\cf2 \strokec2   \
